Tennet is responsible for the transmission of North Sea electricity to the mainland and for its transmission through the German electricity grid.
The wind turbines on the Baltic Sea, which are not part of the Tennet network, have added another 2.22 terawatt hours (TWh) of electricity.
The total wind power from the North and Baltic Seas thus amounts to 13.73 TWh, compared to just over 11.64 TWh in the first half of 2019.
Offshore wind power accounts for almost 19 percent of all wind power in Germany, which is about four percentage points more than a year ago.
New wind farms increase generation capacity
The increase in the contribution of offshore wind energy is due to the increase in generation capacity, as well as to the wind conditions, as new wind farms have been connected to the grid in the past 12 months.
If the 1270 wind turbines in the North Sea were all running at full capacity at the same time, they could generate 6.7 gigawatts of electricity.
The transmission capacity is sufficient for this purpose, and according to Tennet it is 7.1 gigawatts.
By 2030, it is to rise to 17 gigawatts in the German North Sea.
"In Germany and the Netherlands, we are investing €20 billion in expanding offshore grid connections by then", said Tennet's managing director, Tim Meyerjürgens.
In reality, offshore wind farms cannot reach their full capacity, but only about 40 percent.
The previous record day this year is January 2nd, when the North Sea wind farms generated more than 6 gigawatts of electricity.
On average, the North Sea wind turbines produce between 2.5 and 3.0 gigawatts of electricity, the equivalent of three to four nuclear power plants.
This would provide electricity for nearly seven million households.
