Drummer Fleetwood and guitarist Green had formed the now legendary band in London in 1967, and his dreamy instrumental hit "Albatross" is still remembered today.
The life of the musician ("The End of the Game", "In the Skies") was like a roller coaster ride.
With Fleetwood Mac, Green experienced a meteoric rise - the band celebrated their greatest successes but then without him.
There was a dispute, among other things, because Green wanted to donate all the group's profits to charity.
He began to perform in loose robes and with a large crucifix.
Mental problems are also thought to have played a role.
Green left the band in 1970.
There was a social decline.
The blues rock guitarist suffered from drug abuse and schizophrenia, according to biographers.
Green was treated in the psychiatric ward for a long time.
For much of the 1970s, the musician disappeared from the scene.
He is said to have lived on the streets for a time, worked as a cemetery gardener and spent time in an Israeli kibbutz.
Green was born in Bethnal Green, London, to a working-class Jewish family in 1946.
From a young age, he was inspired by American blues musicians such as B.B. King and Muddy Waters.
At the age of eleven, he learned his first guitar moves.
At the age of 15, the teenager began playing guitar professionally and five years later got the chance to perform as lead guitarist for the instrumental band Peter B's Looners.
Shortly after, he was hired as a replacement for his idol Eric Clapton in the Bluesbreakers.
In the midst of the blues boom, Green formed Fleetwood Mac in the summer of 1967 with fellow Bluesbreakers Mick Fleetwood and John McVie.
The song "Albatross", written by Green, gave the group their first number one hit in the winter of 1968/69 and catapulted them to the top of the British music scene.
But his rapid rise soon revealed his dark side: Green's media hype was unable to hold him back, and his experiments with the drug LSD became more and more extreme.
He later commented on the life between music and addiction in an interview: "The worst thing that happened to me in life is the drugs - the best was to land a number one hit".
Towards the end of the decade, Green achieved a surprise cult success with a religious-themed album in 1979.
Fleetwood Mac, meanwhile, were swimming without him in a new formation on a wave of success.
Their 1977 album Rumours sold more than 40 million copies worldwide.
Despite various minor solo successes, Green did not make a major comeback until he got a fresh start with a group of musician friends in 1996.
The British "Daily Telegraph" then spoke of a rock star returning to earth.
Free of drugs, Green released several albums with the Peter Green Splinter Group until the band disbanded in 2004.
For music experts, he was already a blues legend during his lifetime - and with his gentle sound one of the most influential guitarists of the past decades.
